Red Wine Exploration

Red Wine Exploration by Anna Porubova

Dataset Introduction and Statistics

This report explores a dataset containing 1,599 red wines with 1o atributes on the chemical properties of the wine.

Description of attributes:

1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Multivariate Plots Section

I have copied data to a new data frame data_1 and created three factor columns: - alcohol.level accordingly to [https://winefolly.com/tutorial/the-lightest-to-the-strongest-wine/] - quality.level. I divided the total.sulfur.dioxide by median value into two levels, to study more the effect of total.sulfur.dioxide on quality. - quality.level. To avoid overcrowding of plots, I rearranged quality factors into three, instead of 6.

Scatterplot total.sulfur.dioxide, alcohol, quality

Following my previous analysis. I decided to check if there is any relationship between three variables, quality, alcohol and total.sulfur.dioxide. The above plot displays some visible pattern, as two main clusters: beige for mid-range and green for the top. Hence, we can draw some conclusion the better the quality, the higher the alcohol and the lower is total.sulfur.dioxide.

However, after I split data into facet-wrap categories by quality level, We can observe how negative correlation between alcohol and total.sulfur.dioxide changes to positive. Higher grade wine is relatively tolerant to the amount of total.sulfur.dioxide, if alcohol level is high, while mid-low-grade wine insists on a moderate level of total.sulfur.dioxide, regardless of alcohol strength.

Scatterplot pH, fixed.acidity, alcohol, quality

After I facet-wrapped by quality level, I havent noticed a big shift in data position, but observed improvement in the relationship between pH and fixed.acidity, it became almost linear.

Scatterplot pH, fixed.acidity, alcohol

Fixed acidity and Density represent the strongest positive correlation, from another side alcohol and density, share opposite direction trend. Combining all three variables, we can see how the scatter plot change its shape and how trend line sliding from the top left corner to the right bottom based on the wine strength.

Scatterplot pH, density and quality

The pattern can be seen in this plot. The trend quality.level lines are almost parallel and appear in order. The lower the levels of density and the higher level of pH associated with the better quality of a wine.

Reflection

The Red Wine Dataset has 1599 observations and 13 variables, however, most of the observations ( 82.5) fall between 5 and 6 quality levels, which may be biased to make a solid conclusion. However, based on my analysis. I can draw some insights: - The quality is a primary attribute and it is easier to start building connections with other variables from this point. - Quality and Alcohol have a meaningful correlation with the correlation coefficient of 0.48. - Still, the strongest positive correlations present withing acidic and dioxides groups, equal to 0.67. - Fixed acidity, has the strongest negative relationship with pH (-0.68).
This could be expected from bipolar chemical properties. In general, none of the attributes displays very strong correlation.

For my research, I was interested to find a relationship between total sulfur dioxide and quality. Total sulfur dioxide is an important chemical element and plays an important role to preserve the wine, on another hand it can affect the quality of the wine if the concentration is higher than 50 ppm. Looking at the distribution of this property, I could see the change in mean and median values facet-wrapped by the quality levels. But, after bivariate analysis, I couldnt draw any connection between quality and total sulfur dioxide. Only after conducting the multivariate analysis between quality, alcohol and total sulfur dioxide, I was able to detect the pattern in relation to the strength of alcohol and it is behaviour in different quality levels.

For my future project, I would like to work with a larger dataset to avoid the bias and to build a predictive model.
